1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3 e6 7. g4 Be7 8. Bg2
Nfd7 $1 {A necessary retreat in order to prepare Nc6.} 9. Be3 Nc6 10. Qe2 Nxd4
11. Bxd4 O-O 12. O-O (12. O-O-O {leads to different, sharper positions.}) 12...
b5 $1 {Black should not wait to play this move.} ({If} 12... Rb8 13. a4 {
prevents b5.}) 13. e5 d5 (13... dxe5 $5 {is playable, leading to a different
game.}) 14. a3 {b5-b4 was not a big threat, but White aims to prevent Black
from improving his worst piece.} ({Still,} 14. Qe3 $5 {has an interesting
point. After the natural} b4 15. Ne2 a5 16. c4 $1 {is possible} (16. f4 Ba6 17.
Rf2 Rc8 18. Ng3 Rc6 {[%cal Yd8c7] looks nice for Black.}) 16... bxc3 17. Nxc3 {
[%csl Gc3,Gd4] White achieved solid posts for the pieces, but the open lines
on the queenside should give Black equal chances. Haubro,M (2297)-Hagen,A 
(2383)/DEN-chT 1718 56th 2017 (8.4)/1/2-1/2} (17. Bxc3 $6 Ba6 18. Rfe1 Rc8 19.
Nd4 Nc5 $15 {is already pleasant for Black}) 17... Ba6 18. Rfc1 Rc8 19. Na4 (
19. Rc2 Bc5 $1) 19... Rxc1+ 20. Rxc1 Qb8 $1 {[%cal Yf8c8] , and Black is fine.}
) 14... Qc7 15. f4 Bc5 $5 {The exchange of the dark-squared bishops usually
favors White in this structure, but in this position White is not able to
recapture on d4 with the knight, and his king may become a bit unsafe after
the exchange.} 16. Qe3 (16. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 17. Qf2 {would be more precise.} Rb8 (
17... Qxf2+ 18. Rxf2 {[%cal Yc3e2,Ye2d4] helps White}) 18. Qxc5 Nxc5 19. Ne2
Bd7 20. Nd4 Rfc8 {[%cal Yc5a4,Ga6a5,Gb5b4] Black has chances of counterplay on
the queenside with Na4-ideas or a5-b4.}) 16... Bxd4 {Otherwise White will play
Ne2 on the next move.} 17. Qxd4 Bb7 18. Rae1 Rac8 19. Rf2 {Hou probably
realized that the typical f5-breakthrough will not work here.} (19. f5 $6 Qc5
$1 {after the exchange of queens, White loses his prospects of an initiative
on the kingside, and the endgame looks already a bit unpleasant for him in
view of the newly-created weakness on e5 and the constant pressure along the
c-file.} 20. Qxc5 (20. Ne2 $6 {fails to complicate matters.} exf5 21. gxf5 Nxe5
$15) 20... Rxc5 {[%cal Ya6a5,Yb5b4] Ideas with a5-b4 can be already considered.
} 21. fxe6 fxe6 22. Rxf8+ Nxf8 23. Re2 a5 {[%cal Yf8g6,Gb5b4,Yb7a6] , and
Black has the better chances.}) 19... Qb6 $5 {Wang Hao now thought that White
was sufficiently prepared to play f4-f5 and decided to exchange queens on b6,
so the knight can go to c4 quickly.} 20. Qxb6 Nxb6 21. Nd1 {White wants to
secure the queenside first.} (21. f5 $6 {is risky, after} Nc4 22. Nd1 Rfe8 {
[%csl Ye5] White starts to face problems with his structure.}) 21... Na4 $5 {
The start of an interesting idea.} (21... Nc4 {would be the most natural.} 22.
c3 Rfd8 23. Ne3 Rc7 {[%cal Yd5d4] Black is fine, although the position should
be equal with correct play by both sides.}) 22. c3 Nc5 $1 23. Rd2 Nb3 24. Rf2
a5 $1 {[%cal Yb5b4] The knight's manoeuvre had the clear goal of weakening,
blockading and then attacking White's queenside! The b5-b4 threat is already a
bit unpleasant for him.} 25. Ne3 (25. Re3 {[%csl Yd1] prevents the idea for
now, but the knight becomes awkward and Black is able to create other ideas.}
Rfd8 26. Bf1 d4 27. cxd4 Nxd4 28. Nc3 b4 $36) 25... b4 26. axb4 axb4 27. c4 $5
(27. cxb4 $1 {was probably more precise. Although the b4-pawn looks easy to
