{We have a slight imbalance in this position, as Black has the passed d5-pawn
against White's 2x1 on the queenside. The game should be close to equal if
White is able to regroup his pieces. Knowing that, find the best continuation
for Black.} 34... d4 $1 {The best way to create some pressure on White's
position before he is ready to bring back the knight.} (34... Bd7 $6 {[%cal
Ye7c6] , preparing Nc6, is too slow.} 35. Bf1 Bc8 36. Bc5 $1 {, and White has
no problems.} Qc6 (36... Nc6 $4 37. Bxf8 Kxf8 38. Qh7 $18) 37. Qc3 Bb7 38. Bb4
$11) 35. Bf1 (35. Bxc6 Nxc6 36. Ng3 Nb4 $1 {Black has a dangerous initiative
here.} 37. Qxd4 Qf3 38. Qe3 Qd1+ 39. Kg2 Nd3 $17 {[%csl Gb3][%cal Rf8c5]})
35... Bd5 36. Qxa6 (36. Bxd4 Ng6 $36 {Preserves nice chances of an initiative
for Black}) 36... Qxb3 37. Qd3 Qxa4 38. Qxd4 Qa8 $40 {[%cal Ye7c6,Ga8a4,Ga4e4]
Black demonstrated in a very impressive way how risky White's position is:
Despite the simplifications, his pawns can be more easily attacked, the
kingside is weakened and Black can create threats making use of the open
diagonals, with Nc6 and Qa4-e4. Actually, this was the winning plan for Black
in Howell,D (2611)-Carlsen,M (2802)/London Classic 2nd 2010 (5)/0-1} *

