{[%csl Yd5,Gd6,Ye4,Ge5,Yg2] We have seen similar structures in other Najdorf
lines, but the pawns on h3/g4 suggest that this one arises from the 6.h3
variation. All the features examined previously can be pointed out here: both
sides have potentially weak pawns (d6,e4) and both sides have a solid outpost
for the pieces (e5,d5). Still, I think the differences are slightly in Black's
favor. The white bishop seems inferor on g2, while the advanced pawns on the
kingside only weaken the dark squares. In this case, I like Black's chances,
because the weak squares on the kingside have a long-term character. If Black
is able to put pressure in both flanks at the right moment, White will be in
an unpleasant defensive task.}  *

