2-1/2}) 12... e5 $1 {This basically ends any potential of White's kingside
pawns.} 13. Qd2 exf4 14. Bxf4 Ne5 {[%csl Ye5] A typical structure has been
reached. Black has no serious problems on d6, and the knight has a nice post
on e5. The advanced pawns on the kingside give me the impression that White
created unnecessary weaknesses in his camp, although the position should be
objectively balanced.} 15. Nd5 {Of course White has the nice square d5 as well.
} Be6 16. Nxe7+ {This exchange might look strange at first sight, but White
eliminates one defender of d6 and ensures that his dark-squared bishop will be
able to protect the weak squares in his camp.} Qxe7 17. Rad1 Rfd8 18. Rf2 $5 {
This rook might be useful on the second rank if White achieves an ideal set-up,
like Qb4, Rfd2.} (18. a4 {also makes sense, trying to cramp the queenside:} Qc7
19. Rf2 h6 20. b3 b5 21. axb5 axb5 22. Qd4 Rd7 23. Bf1 Rb8 24. Qe3 f6 $1 {
[%cal Yb8e8,Ye6f7,Yf7g6] , preventing g5-ideas. Black's position is safe and
he can change plans at the right moment, for example with Re8-Bf7-g6. Still
the position looks equal, but compared to the game we will see that the
absence of the a-pawns makes White's life easier. Deepan Chakkravarthy,J (2496)
-Adhiban,B (2608)/Kolkata op 19th 2014 (8)/0-1}) 18... b5 19. b3 {White's
queenside is safe, but not without weaknesses.} ({Maybe White should play} 19.
g5 $5 {, which does not bring any advantage, but prevents Black from achieving
the ideal formation on the kingside, as he did in the game.} Rac8 20. b3 Re8 $5
21. Qb4 (21. Qxd6 $2 Rcd8 $19 {[%csl Rd1]}) 21... Ng6 $1 22. Be3 Red8 {The
position remains tense, but White still needs to be aware, for example} 23.
Rfd2 $2 Nh4 $1 24. Rxd6 Re8 $1 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Yh4g2]} 25. R1d2 Bf5 $1 {
, and Black has a dangerous initiative.}) 19... Qc7 20. Qe3 Rd7 21. Rfd2 h6 $1
22. Qf2 (22. g5 $2 {is just bad now:} hxg5 23. Bxg5 f6 24. Bf4 Kf7 $1 {[%cal
Ya8h8]}) 22... f6 $1 {[%csl Ge5,Yg5][%cal Ye6f7,Yf7g6] The last two moves were
very important to secure a small but real advantage for Black. The Ne5 is
reinforced now and g5-ideas are definitely prevented. White is still solid,
but it is difficult to imagine how to improve his position or even find active
ideas. On the other hand, life is much easier for Black, as besides the ideas
on the queenside, he can slowly build pressure against e4. I think White
should be ok with correct play, but in practice, such a position tends to be
unpleasant to play.} 23. Rd4 Rc8 24. Qd2 $2 {White already went wrong. There
was no reason to change the set-up.} (24. R4d2 {was better, but then Black can
keep improving his pieces:} Qb8 $1 {[%cal Yc8c3]} 25. Qd4 Rc6 26. Qe3 Qc7 27.
Qf2 a5 28. Bf1 Qb8 $15 {Black is better, but I don't see anything concrete yet.
}) 24... Nf7 $5 (24... Qc5 $1 {was even stronger.} 25. Kh1 (25. Be3 Bf7 $1 26.
Rxd6 $2 Rxd6 $19) 25... Rc6 $1 {Black is preparing to take on c2 under better
circumstances.} 26. Rc1 Qa7 27. Rd1 Qc7 28. Rc1 Rc3 $17) 25. Kh1 $2 {Maybe
White misevaluated the dangers of this position.} (25. Rc1 {would offer better
resistance.} Qd8 26. Kh1 Rc5 $5 {[%cal Yh6h5,Gd8c7]}) 25... Qxc2 26. Bxd6 a5 $1
{Black has the simple and winning idea of fixing the a2-pawn, against which
White is defenceless.} (26... Rc6 {wins a pawn, but after} 27. Bg3 Rxd4 28.
Qxd4 Qxa2 29. e5 $1 Rc2 30. Bd5 {White gets some counterplay.}) 27. Bf1 (27.
Qxa5 $2 {loses due to} Rxd6 $1 28. Rxd6 Nxd6 29. Rxd6 Qc1+ 30. Kh2 Qf4+ $19)
27... b4 $19 {[%csl Ra2] White has no way to avoid losing the a2-pawn, which
means a quick collapse of the position. Now we can see why he should had
played a2-a4 on move 19.} 28. Bb5 (28. Bg2 Rc6 29. e5 $2 fxe5 $19) (28. Bc5
Qxd2 29. R1xd2 Rxc5 30. Rxd7 Bxd7 31. Rxd7 Rc1 32. Kg2 Rc2+ 33. Kg3 Ne5 $1 $19)
28... Rdd8 29. Qxc2 Rxc2 30. Bf4 Rxd4 31. Rxd4 Rxa2 32. Ba4 {White puts his
hopes on a fortress, but there are too many weaknesses in his position to make
it possible.} Rc2 {[%cal Yc2c3]} 33. Rd3 g5 $1 34. Bd2 (34. Bb8 Rc3 {is
Black's idea.} 35. Rxc3 bxc3 36. Ba7 Ne5 37. Be3 Bd7 $1 $19) 34... Ne5 35. Rd6
Nf3 0-1

