{[%csl Gd2,Ye4][%cal Yc2c3,Gf8h6,Gb8d7,Gd7c5,Gb1d2,Gf1d3] Although the line
has barely reached its childhood in tournament practice, we can call this
structure "typical" for the 6.a3 line. The result is a middlegame with
opposite-colored bishops and interesting possibilities. Black normally
develops his bishop actively on h6 and the knight via d7-c5. The advance e5-e4
would be desirable under favorable circumstances, of course, but White
normally organizes his pieces on light-squares (Bd3,Nd2), making it hard.
Another idea for White is to undermine Black's structure by means of c2-c3, in
order to get more freedom to his pieces. The open g-file normally leads to
positions with both sides castling to the queenside. Nevertheless, often Black
keeps his king in the center. Black should prevent White from establishing a
strong knight on e4. That is why he should part with the bishop to exchange
that knight. After the eventual exchange of the queens, the endgames with
knight versus bishop with rooks on the board are balanced. Black has no
problems if he is able to coordinate the pieces, as the knight has nice
squares like c5 or b6.}  *

