1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. a3 $5 e5 7. Nf5 d5 $1 8.
Bg5 d4 9. Bxf6 gxf6 $1 (9... Qxf6 10. Nd5 Qd8 11. Qg4 $36 {gave White the
initiative in Carlsen,M (2840) -Wojtaszek,R (2750)/Tata Steel-A 79th 2017 (2)/
1-0.}) 10. Nb1 Bxf5 $5 {This is a concrete solution for Black, as the knight
would stay permanently well placed on f5.} 11. exf5 Qd5 $1 (11... Qa5+ $6 {
This would be imprecise because White has} 12. c3 $1 Nc6 13. Bd3 {with good
development, for example} O-O-O 14. O-O dxc3 15. Nxc3 $14 {[%cal Yd1e2,Yd3e4]})
12. Qd3 Qa5+ $5 {Now this check is correct.} 13. Nd2 (13. c3 Nc6 {[%csl Yd3,
Yf1] The queen is in the way of the bishop, which makes a considerable
difference.} 14. Be2 O-O-O 15. O-O Qc7 16. Bf3 dxc3 17. Qxc3 Nd4 $13) 13... Bb4
$5 {Black goes for simplification at the first chance.} ({I think} 13... Nd7 {
would be more precise.} 14. O-O-O (14. Be2 Bb4 $1 {This seems an improvement
for Black compared to the game.} 15. O-O-O Nc5 16. Qf3 Bxd2+ 17. Rxd2 Qc7 18.
Kb1 O-O-O {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yd8d7,Yh8d8,Ye5e4,Yc7e5] Black is at least fine,
he has the simple plan of Rd7-Rhd8-e4, with powerful play in the centre.})
14... Bh6 $1 {This exchange is necessary for Black.} 15. Kb1 Nc5 16. Qe2 Bxd2
17. Qxd2 $2 (17. Rxd2 $142 O-O $5 18. h4 Rad8 19. Rh3 Kh8 $13) 17... Qxd2 18.
Rxd2 {Black has a strong idea now:} Ne4 $1 19. Re2 Nd6 {[%csl Yf5] , and
Black's play is already easier, for example} 20. g4 O-O-O 21. Bg2 Rhg8 22. Bf3
h5 23. h3 Kc7 $14) 14. O-O-O Bxd2+ 15. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 16. Rxd2 Nd7 {Comparing this
position with the lines analysed in the previous note, Black is not so active
now.} 17. Bc4 $5 Rc8 18. Bd5 {[%csl Gb7,Yd5,Gf7] White hopes to keep Black
under pressure on both sides.} Rc7 19. Re1 Kf8 {Black will have some problems
to coordinate the pieces after this move.} ({But} 19... O-O {looks better.
Black would not have faced the problems seen in the game.}) 20. f4 $1 {White
makes use of his lead in development, posing some problems for Black.} Rg8 21.
Kb1 b5 22. g3 a5 (22... Kg7 $1 {was probably better, solving Black's
development.} 23. fxe5 fxe5 24. f6+ $1 Kg6 $1 (24... Kxf6 25. Rf1+ {[%csl Rf7]}
) 25. Be4+ Kxf6 26. Bxh7 Rh8 27. Rf2+ Ke7 28. Bf5 f6 29. h4 Nb6 $13 {[%csl Ge3]
[%cal Yb6d5,Yb6c4] The endgame looks a bit complex, but Black has enough
counterplay with the knight coming to e3.}) 23. Rf2 $1 h6 $2 {Areshchenko
fails to see White's idea.} (23... Rc5 $1 {was the right move, winning time
and expelling the bishop from its active position.} 24. Bg2 b4 $1 25. axb4 axb4
26. fxe5 fxe5 27. f6 {This idea is not so strong now, as after} Rg6 28. Ref1
Rh6 29. Be4 {Black has the nice idea} Ra5 $1 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Ya5a6] , and
White is not able to make progress.} 30. Bc6 Nb8 31. Be4 Nd7 32. Bc6 $11) 24.
fxe5 fxe5 (24... Nxe5 {The knight is well placed on e5, but White can change
his attention towards d4 now.} 25. Rd1 Rg4 26. Bg2 Rd7 27. Bf1 Rd5 28. c3 $1 d3
29. Rfd2 $14 {[%csl Rd3]}) 25. f6 $1 {[%csl Yf6] Maybe Black is fine with
correct defence, but his position seems a bit unpleasant already.} Rg6 26. Ref1
Nb6 27. Be4 {[%csl Gh6] If the pawn were still on h7, Black would like to
place his rook there.} Rg4 28. Bd3 $1 Nc4 (28... b4 $2 {would be bad now:} 29.
Re2 Rc5 30. axb4 axb4 31. Ka2 $16 {[%cal Ya2b3] , and Black has new problems
with the b4-pawn.}) 29. Re1 Rc5 30. a4 $1 {A very technical and well-timed
move: White not only prevents Ne3 but also puts Black before a difficult
choice.} Nd6 (30... bxa4 31. Bxc4 Rxc4 32. Rxe5 $18 {looks like a winning
endgame for White.}) 31. axb5 (31. Rfe2 $1 {would be more accurate. If} Rg5 32.
axb5 Nxb5 33. h4 $1 Rxg3 34. Rxe5 Rxe5 35. Rxe5 {White wins.} Nc7 36. Rc5 Ne8
37. Rc8 {[%cal Yd3b5]} h5 38. Bb5 Re3 39. Ka2 Re5 40. Bd7 Re3 41. b3 $18) 31...
e4 32. Be2 Rgg5 33. Rd1 {Although Black achieved some apparent activity, White
has everything under control and the central pawns are weak now.} Rgd5 34. Rf4
a4 35. b6 Rc6 36. c4 $1 {A nice tactical idea to finish the game.} Nxc4 37. b7
$1 Rb5 38. Rxd4 Rxb2+ 39. Ka1 Kg8 40. Rg4+ 1-0

