{[%csl Yb1,Yc4,Gd5,Ye5][%cal Yg2g4,Yg4g5,Yh3h4,Yb7b5,Yb5b4,Gc8c1,Gd4f5,Gc3d5,
Gf6d7,Gd7b6,Gb6c4] This structure resembles a bit the Position 2 but there is
an important difference - White has castled to the queenside and therefore the
position is more complicated. White has clear intentions on the kingside where
he can advance the g and h-pawns and increase the pressure with the maneuver
Nd4-f5. If he is able to get more open files, then his attacking chances would
be very promising. White can also look for a positional advantage with an
early Nd5. In this case, however, Black obtains a solid position after the
exchange Bxd5. Naturally, Black has counter-chances on the queenside. A
typical idea is Nf6-d7-b6 when the knight can go to either (most likely) c4 or
a4. Meanwhile, the other knight stays on e5, thus keeping the kingside
defended. Sacrifices on c3 might be considered as well. The advance of the
b-pawn is also an option, although the queen on b6 sometimes offers nice ideas
combined with ...Nc4. Overall, these positions look dynamically balanced, but
the game normally takes a sharp character full of complications and tactical
ideas.}  *

