) 14... O-O 15. g4 Re8 {[%cal Ye8e1] The rook is always useful on the e-file.}
16. Nd4 {[%csl Gf5] After some improvements, White turns his attention to the
kingside.} Qa5 $1 {[%csl Ga2,Rc3] Renewing the threat of Rxc3.} 17. a3 Bf8 {
Black's moves are very precise and logical: He anticipates Nf5.} 18. Qe1 $6 {
This looks passive.} (18. Nf5 {is harmless now in view of} Nb6 $1 {[%cal Ye5c4]
with nice counterplay.} 19. Qd4 Nec4 20. Bd2 Nxd2+ 21. Rxd2 Red8 $15 {[%cal
Yg7g6,Yf8g7]}) 18... b5 {Black's initiative will come first.} 19. Bg2 $6 {
I think the bishop should have kept an eye on c4.} ({White should go directly
for} 19. Nd5 Qxe1 (19... Qd8 {After this retreat, Black is not able to create
any serious threat.} 20. Qg3 Nb6 21. Bg2 $14) 20. Rxe1 Ng6 21. Bg3 Bxd5 22.
exd5 Rxe1+ 23. Bxe1 Re8 24. Bd2 Nb6 {[%csl Yd5] This looks good for Black, but
after} 25. Nc6 (25. Bg2 $2 Nc4 26. Bc1 Nh4 $17) 25... Nxd5 26. c4 $1 {White
has the initiative.} bxc4 27. Bxc4 Nc7 28. Nb4 $36) 19... Nc4 20. Nd5 Qd8 $5 {
Areschchenko plays ambitiously and keeps the queens on the board.} 21. Qg3 Nc5
$1 {Compared to the notes of White's 19th move, Black is more active now.} 22.
g5 $6 (22. Bc1 $5 {would be good prophylaxis for White.}) 22... Bxd5 $5 {
This exchange was more or less necessary to activate the queen again.} 23. exd5
Qb6 (23... g6 {[%cal Yf8g7] was already good.}) 24. Nc6 a5 (24... g6 $1 {
would be strong again. If} 25. Bc1 Bg7 26. b3 Na4 $1 {, and Black's attack is
very strong, for example} 27. Rd3 Ne5 $1 28. Re3 (28. bxa4 bxa4+ 29. Ka2 Nxd3
30. Qxd3 Rxc6 $1 31. dxc6 Rb8 32. c4 Qf2+ 33. Qd2 Qg3 $1 34. Qc2 Qe5 $19) 28...
Nxc6 29. dxc6 Qd4 30. c3 Nxc3+ 31. Rxc3 Qxc3 $19) 25. Bc1 $1 {White has time
to secure the queenside now.} b4 (25... g6 $5 {was still playable.}) 26. Bf1 $2
{But he missed a strong idea for Black in this position.} (26. Rd4 $1 {[%csl
Gc4] was the right move, immediatelly exploiting the drawback of Black's last
move.} Ne5 {After this retreat Black's initiative is not so strong.} (26...
