{[%csl Gb3][%cal Ya6a5,Ya5a4,Yf7f5,Gf1d3,Gb3d2,Gd2e4,Gc8a6,Gc8b7,Gd2c4] This
structure is often seen in the 6.Be3 variation when White combines the moves 8.
h3, 9.Qf3 and the advance g2-g4; Black responds by quickly pushing his b-pawn.
After an exchange of the knights on d5, we have the current structure. White's
chances of attack in this structure are not great, in my opinion, as despite
having lost the defender on f6, Black has not weak squares around the king.
Besides the typical advance a5-a4, there are two good ideas to deprive White
from looking for an advantage:  1) ...Ba6, exchanging the light-squared bishop
which is important for White's kingside play. 2) A well-timed breakthrough
f7-f5 which makes the game a bit double-edged as White gets the open g-file,
but Black can safely defend g7 with ...Rf7-Bf8, and White's structure looks a
bit exposed now. Since the attack doesn't looks so promising, White can go for
a positional approach, improving the knight via either d2-e4 or d2-c4, thus
exploiting the slightly better structure and space advantage. However, this is
a bit slow and after the aforementioned Ba6-idea, Black has time to work on
the queenside with the simple and strong idea of advancing the a and b-pawns.} 
*

