1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. h3
Be7 9. Qf3 O-O 10. O-O-O b5 11. g4 b4 $1 {Otherwise Black would lose control
over d5.} 12. Nd5 Nxd5 $1 (12... Bxd5 $2 13. exd5 {leaves the light-squares
terribly exposed.}) 13. exd5 Bc8 $1 {[%cal Ya6a5,Ya5a4,Gc8a6,Gc8b7] The bishop
goes back, but this is not a problem: Black has the idea a5-Ba6 now.} 14. Kb1 (
14. Bd3 {is the most played, but after} a5 15. Nd2 Ba6 $1 {[%cal Ya5a4,Yb4b3,
Gd8c7,Gf8c8] I like Black's chances.}) 14... a5 15. Nc5 $5 {White chooses the
trickiest path to improve the knight - this also prevents the bishop from
coming to a6 for one move.} ({Another instructive game went} 15. Bd3 Ba6 $1 16.
h4 Qc7 17. Qe4 Bxd3 18. cxd3 $6 Nd7 19. Rc1 Qb7 20. Bg5 (20. Rc6 {looks nice,
but White is not able to support the outpost.} a4 21. Nd2 Nf6 22. Qc4 Ra5 $1 {
[%csl Rd5]}) {Now with the strong idea} 20... f6 $1 21. Be3 a4 22. Nd2 f5 $1
23. gxf5 Nf6 $17 {[%csl Gd5] Black had a big advantage in Alonso,S (2521)
-Mareco,S (2580)/Montevideo zt 2.5 2013 (4)/1-0.}) 15... a4 (15... dxc5 $6 16.
d6 Ra7 17. dxe7 Qxe7 18. Bc4 $44 {[%cal Yh1e1] offers White nice compensation.}
) 16. Ne4 Ba6 $1 {At first sight this might look a bit weird, since Black
stays with the "bad bishop", but it is important to prevent White from
developing play on the light-squares. Another point is that Black's
mobilization on the queenside is accelerated.} 17. g5 {Curiously, the natural
idea of advancing the kingside pawns is not so good, as we will see.} Nd7 18.
h4 ({White has an interesting way to organize his pieces in this position:} 18.
Bxa6 Rxa6 19. Qg4 Qc7 20. Rd3 $1 {This rook is very useful on the third rank,
keeping an eye on both of the board} Nb6 21. Bxb6 Rxb6 22. Rc1 {White has no
problems with the king's safety now and may continue advancing the pawns on
the kingside.} (22. Nf6+ Kh8 23. Nd7 $2 {This "nice" trick backfires after} Rc8
$1 {[%csl Gc2,Rd7][%cal Yb6b7]}) 22... Kh8 $1 23. h4 Qc4 {[%cal Yb4b3]} 24. Rd2
Rbb8 (24... Rb5 $2 25. Qd7 $1) 25. h5 Qc8 $5 $13 {[%cal Yf7f5]}) 18... Bxf1 19.
Rhxf1 Qc7 {Both sides have played natural moves according to their respective
plans, and yet the position seems easier to handle as Black. Although White
has not done anything wrong, his position looks just harder to improve while
Black's ideas on the queenside already seem promising.} 20. Qe2 $2 {The first
serious mistake. White's position becomes too passive now.} (20. Bd2 $5 {
would be a better try, with the possible follow-up} b3 $5 (20... Rfc8 21. Qd3 {
and now} b3 $5 22. cxb3 axb3 23. Qxb3 Rcb8 {transposes}) (20... Rfb8 $5 {
is also possible, keeping the tension.}) 21. cxb3 axb3 22. Qxb3 Rfb8 {Black
sacrificed the pawn to get strong pressure on the open lines on the queenside,
but White should be able to defend with careful play.} 23. Qc2 Qa7 (23... Qb7
24. Bc3 f5 25. gxf6 Nxf6 26. Nxf6+ Bxf6 27. Rfe1 {, and White still holds the
initiative, for example} Qa7 28. b3 Rc8 {[%cal Ye5e4]} 29. Re4 $1) 24. b3 (24.
Nc3 Bd8 $1 {[%cal Gd8a5]} 25. Be3 Bb6 26. Bxb6 Nxb6 $17) 24... f5 $1 25. gxf6 (
25. Nc3 $2 g6 $1 {[%cal Ye7f8,Yf8g7,Gd7c5] Black is able to increase the
pressure by improving his minor pieces.}) 25... Nxf6 26. Nxf6+ Bxf6 27. Be3 Qa5
$13 {The position remains tense but White is probably able to keep defending
the important points on the queenside.}) 20... Rfc8 21. Rc1 f5 $1 {White
probably missed this idea, as apparently the main battle is taking place on
the queenside. His position becomes very difficult now.} 22. gxf6 (22. Ng3 $2
f4 23. Nf5 Bf8 24. Bd2 Qb7 {Black is simply winning.} 25. h5 Rab8 {[%cal Gb7d5]
} 26. Qd3 Rc5 27. g6 h6 $19) 22... Nxf6 23. Ng5 $2 (23. Nxf6+ {was White's
best chance.} Bxf6 {, but White faces many unpleasant problems in this
position, for example} 24. Bd2 (24. c4 bxc3 25. Rxc3 Qb7 {[%csl Rd5,Rh4][%cal
Ge5e4]}) 24... Rab8 25. Qd3 Qc4 $1 $17 {White will find the endgames equally
sad to defend, in view of his very bad structure.}) 23... a3 $1 $19 {The
attack on the queenside is too strong and White can't avoid material losses.}
24. Ne6 (24. c4 bxc3 25. Rxc3 Qb7 26. Rb3 Qxd5 $19) 24... Qa5 25. b3 Qxd5 {
The rest was just white suffering.} 26. Ng5 h6 27. Rcd1 Qc6 28. Ne6 Ne4 29. Rd3
Nc3+ 30. Rxc3 Qxc3 31. Bc1 Bf6 0-1

