{[%csl Gb1,Yd5,Gg8][%cal Yg1g8] At first sight, this structure resembles those
already seen in databases 1 and 2, but the position is simply different. The
opposite castles suggest a sharper game by nature. White has also sacrificed
the g4-pawn in order to get an open file on the kingside. In my opinion, this
is not enough to claim an advantage for White. In practice, however, his moves
are very easy and the task of the defender might be a bit unpleasant. Black
has enough defensive resources to deal with White's attack. After securing the
king, he is ready to use his extra pawn and to create counter-chances on the
queenside. One important thing to remember for Black is that White's ideal
set-up would be keeping heavy pieces and the strong Nd5 against the bad bishop.
In this case, Black would have trouble to simultaneously deal with the
positional pressure and White's initiative. Therefore, Black should keep his
only knight on the board, and in the worst scenario, prevent the remaining
opponent's knight from coming to d5.}  *

