17. Rxd6 $18) 15. Rdxf1 h6 $1 {[%cal Ge7g5] Black uses the position of the
opponent's king in his favor.} 16. Kb1 Bg5 17. Qf2 Rc8 18. Nd5 Nf6 {now, one
game went} 19. h4 Nxd5 20. hxg5 Nf4 $1 21. gxh6 gxh6 {[%csl Gf4,Yh6] Black
kept the extra pawn and had a good position in Iljiushenok,I (2427)
-Areshchenko,A (2710)/Chigorin Memorial 20th 2012 (3)/0-1.}) 11... O-O 12. f5
Bc4 13. g4 $5 Nxg4 14. Rg1 Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Bxb3 $1 {This is the right exchange
now, as the light-squared bishop is useless for White's attacking purposes on
the kingside.} 16. Qh6 $2 (16. axb3 Kh8 17. Nd5 {This is the best option for
White, but he has no more than sufficient compensation for the pawn.} Nf6 18.
Qg3 Rg8 {We can see how impotent White's bishop is in this position.}) 16...
Bxc2+ $1 {This is possible when White plays 11.Kb1 - now his king is exposed,
too.} 17. Kxc2 Bf6 18. Rxd6 (18. Rd3 {wouldn't help White,} Kh8 19. Qh5 h6 $1
20. Rh3 Kh7 {, and the "attack" is at a dead point.} 21. Nd5 Rc8+ 22. Kb1 Nb6
23. Ne3 (23. Rxg7+ Bxg7 24. f6 Nxd5 25. fxg7 Qf6 $1 26. gxf8=N+ Rxf8 $17) 23...
Qc7 24. Bd3 Qc5 {Black is active now. After} 25. Re1 {[%cal Ye3g4] White can
hope to organize some threats, but I think the following line illustrates well
that this is not enough:} Kg8 $1 26. Rg3 (26. Ng4 Bg5 {[%cal Gc5c1]}) 26...
Rfd8 $1 27. Qxh6 Kf8 $17 {[%cal Gf8e7,Yd6d5] Suddenly the king will find a
safe place on e7 and Black is ready to break through in the centre with d6-d5,
taking a strong initiative.}) 18... Kh8 19. Qd2 Ra7 $17 {Now Black is much
better. (Karjakin)} 20. Kb1 (20. Qg2 Rg8 21. Rd3 Be7 $17) (20. Nd5 Qc8+ 21. Kb1
Qc5 $1 {[%csl Gd6,Gg1]} 22. Ne3 Rc8 $17) 20... Qc7 21. Rd3 Nb6 22. Nd5 Nxd5 23.
Rxd5 {White places his hopes now on the opposite-colored bishops, but
Karjakin's technique is very precise.} Rd8 24. Be2 Rxd5 25. Qxd5 g6 26. Rc1 Qe7
27. Qc5 (27. Qc6 Kg7 28. Qb6 Bg5 $17) 27... Kg7 28. Qxe7 Bxe7 29. Rc6 Kh6 $1 {
The king marches to invade White's kingside.} 30. a4 $2 {The decisive mistake.
(Karjakin).} ({White should have played} 30. fxg6 {and if} hxg6 (30... fxg6 31.
Re6) {then} 31. a4 {with drawing chances.}) 30... bxa4 31. Rxa6 $2 ({But} 31.
fxg6 fxg6 32. Bxa6 {does not help much either.} Kg5 $17) 31... Rxa6 32. Bxa6
Kg5 33. fxg6 fxg6 $1 {The point! Now White has no defence against Kh4 followed
by g5, g4, Kh3.} 34. Kc2 Kh4 35. Bc8 (35. Bf1 g5 36. Kc3 g4 37. Kc4 Bg5 $19 {
[%cal Rg5f4]}) 35... g5 36. Kd3 g4 37. Kc4 Kh3 {In view of the inevitable h5
and Kxh2 White resigned!} 0-1

