{[%cal Yg2g4,Yf3f4,Gh5h4,Gd7b6,Gb6c4,Yb5b4] When Black answers the sharp lines
of the English Attack with 8...h5 and White refrains from provoking the
transformation of the pawn structure by means of Nd5, this structure may arise.
White hopes to use the h5-pawn as a hook to open files on the kingside with
g2-g4. The advance f3-f4 is also an idea if Black keeps the king in the centre.
Black has the typical ideas on the queenside with (b5-b4, Nb6-c4), but an
extra idea in this position is to paralyze White's kingside with h5-h4.
Although some grandmasters have played this set-up to avoid the main
theoretical lines, I think Black is fine, and the positions tend to be
balanced.}  *

