h5 $5 {A solid option for Black.} 9. Qd2 Nbd7 10. O-O-O Be7 11. Kb1 Rc8 12. f4
$5 {White goes for a different plan.} (12. h3 {is another move order.} b5 13.
Bd3 {[%cal Yf3f4,Yg2g4] White's plans are more flexible now, as g2-g4 can be
considered, although I think Black is fine here too.} Nb6 $5 (13... h4 {
is mostly played.}) 14. g4 (14. f4 Qc7 {transposes to the game.}) 14... b4 $146
{an interesting idea.} 15. Ne2 Nc4 16. Bxc4 Bxc4 17. Ng3 g6 {, and Black is ok,
for example} 18. Qxb4 $2 h4 $1 19. Nf1 Be2 $17 {[%csl Rd1,Rf3]}) 12... b5 13.
Bd3 Qc7 14. h3 Nb6 $5 {Black plays actively.} ({The solid} 14... h4 {is mostly
played.}) 15. Bxb6 {White should avoid the knight from coming to c4.} (15. f5
$2 Nc4 16. Bxc4 Bxc4 $15 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Yb5b4] is already better for Black.})
15... Qxb6 16. Nd5 $6 {Now White tries to open the centre, but this was not a
good moment.} (16. g4 $6 {was played once, hoping to increase the tension, but
after the forced sequence} b4 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. exd5 Bxd5 19. Bxa6 Bxh1 20. Bxc8
{Dubiel,J (2359)-Jakubowski,T (2311)/POL-chT 56th 2000 (5)/1-0} Bf3 $1 21. Re1
Bh4 $1 22. Rf1 e4 $15 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ye8g8] Black's position seems easier.})
(16. Rhe1 {looks more natural, bringing another rook to the centre before
opening the central file.} Qc7 $5 17. a3 (17. Nd5 $6 {is harmless now:} Nxd5
18. exd5 Bxd5 19. Bxb5+ $2 axb5 {[%csl Gc2]}) 17... h4 18. Qe2 Kf8 $13) 16...
Bxd5 17. exd5 e4 $1 18. Be2 h4 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Gh4] With the last two moves,
Black managed to prevent White's ideas in both the centre and the kingside and
already has a good position.} 19. Qd4 Qc7 $2 {But this was a wrong step.} (
19... Bd8 $1 {[%cal Yd8b6] would be a clever idea.} 20. a4 O-O $1 {Black
sacrifices one pawn but gets a real compensation, for example} 21. Qxb6 Bxb6
22. axb5 axb5 23. Bxb5 Nh5 $1 24. Nd2 (24. Rhf1 Ng3 25. Rfe1 Bf2 $17 {[%csl
Re1]}) 24... f5 25. Nc4 Bc5 26. Rhf1 Rc7 $1 27. Bc6 Re7 $17 {[%cal Ge4e3,Ye7e4]
Black's pieces are much more active.}) 20. Rc1 $5 {[%cal Yc2c4] White is
looking for activity.} (20. c3 {[%cal Yb3d2] wins a pawn, but after} O-O 21.
Nd2 Rfe8 22. Nxe4 Nxe4 23. Qxe4 Bf6 24. Qc2 b4 $36 {Black's initiative on the
queenside is enough compensation.}) 20... O-O 21. c4 b4 $2 (21... Qd7 $1 {
[%cal Yd7f5] was a better option.}) 22. Rhg1 (22. g4 $1 {was more precise.
This way White would have prevented the idea seen in the game.} hxg3 (22... Nd7
23. g5 $1 {[%csl Re4,Yf6,Rh4] The bishop can't go to f6 now and the pawns are
doomed to fall.}) 23. Rhg1 Nd7 24. Rxg3 Bf6 25. Qxe4 $14 {[%cal Yg1g8] With
the open g-file White has a much better version of the game now.}) 22... Nd7 $5
{Black probably has some practical chances with this sacrifice, although it is
clear that the advantage is with White.} 23. Qxe4 Bf6 24. g4 Nc5 $5 {Black
keeps the kingside as closed as possible, hoping that the opposite-colored
bishops might give him chances of counterplay or at least complicate matters.}
25. Nxc5 Qxc5 26. Bd3 $2 {This aggressive-looking move is actually a mistake,
which surprisingly loses all White's advantage.} (26. g5 $1 {was more direct:}
Rce8 27. Qc2 $1 Bd4 28. Rg2 Re3 (28... g6 29. f5 $18) 29. g6 $1 f5 30. Bd3 $18
{[%cal Yc2d1,Yd1h5,Gd3f5]}) 26... g6 27. g5 Rce8 $2 ({Both sides missed the
spectacular idea} 27... Bxb2 $3 28. Kxb2 Rfe8 29. Qf3 Re3 30. Qd1 Qd4+ 31. Kc2
Rxd3 $1 32. Qxd3 Rxc4+ 33. Qxc4 Qxc4+ $19) 28. Qg2 {[%csl Yg2] It turns out
that the queen is misplaced on g2.} Bd4 29. Rgf1 Re3 {One by one, Black
improves his pieces.} 30. Rcd1 Bg7 $2 {After this careless retreat, the
evaluation of the position changes again.} ({In positions like this 
(opposite-colored bishops with heavy pieces on the board) everything is about
how quickly both sides can develop the initiative, therefore Black should
hurry to open more files for the attack with} 30... b3 $1 31. axb3 ({A nice
detail is that after} 31. a3 $2 Bg7 $1 {works.} 32. f5 Qd4 {[%csl Yc2] The
queen is deprived of c2, where it would defend all the attacked points.} 33.
Qf2 Be5 $19) 31... Rb8 32. Qc2 a5 $1 {[%cal Ga5a4] . and Black keeps strong
pressure on the queenside.}) 31. f5 $1 gxf5 (31... Qd4 $2 {is harmless now in
view of} 32. Qc2 $16) 32. Qf2 $1 {White has taken things under control again,
although the position remains tense.} Qd4 33. Bxf5 Qe5 34. Rd2 (34. Rde1 {
was perhaps safer.}) 34... Qg3 $5 {A good practical decision.} (34... b3 35.
Qxh4 {would be risky now.}) 35. Bg4 {I have the impression that things went
slightly out of control for both players from now, maybe due to mutual time
trouble.} (35. c5 $5 dxc5 36. d6 Bd4 37. d7 $16) 35... a5 (35... b3 $1) 36. Bh5
(36. c5 $1) 36... f5 37. Re2 f4 $2 (37... Qxf2 38. Rexf2 Rxh3 $15) 38. Rxe3 $2
{Now, Bologan lost control and the game.} (38. Bg4 $142) 38... fxe3 39. Bf7+ (
39. Qe2 Qxh3 $17) 39... Kh8 40. Qe2 Qxg5 $19 41. Kc1 a4 42. Rf3 a3 43. bxa3 Qe5
44. axb4 Qa1+ 45. Kc2 Qb2+ 46. Kd3 Qc3+ 0-1

