{[#]} {White's last move 18.Bg5 creates some problems for Black: b4 is now
hanging, the d6 pawn is hanging after the exchange on f6 and White has the
maneuver Nf1-e3 in mind at some point. How should Black respond?} 18... h4 $1 (
18... a5 $2 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. gxh5 gxh5 $2 21. Nf5 $18) 19. Bxf6 (19. Nf1 Nxe4
$1 $17) 19... Bxf6 20. Nf1 Bg5 $1 21. Qxb4 (21. Qxd6 $2 Qxd6 22. Rxd6 Ke7 23.
Rd1 Rhd8 $19 {Black is too far ahead in development.}) 21... O-O $1 {The
bishop pair and better development give Black nice compensation here.} 22. Nfd2
(22. Rxd6 $2 Qxd6 $1 23. Qxd6 Rfd8 {[%cal Yd8d1]} 24. Qxd8+ Rxd8 25. Nh2 Bf4 {
[%csl Rh2] Despite being two pawns up, White is a piece down in practice with
such a dominated knight.} 26. g5 Be2 $19) 22... Be6 23. Rhe1 Qd7 $17 {[%cal
Yc8b8,Yf8c8] Black has nice initiative for the pawn.} *

