{[%csl Gb5,Gc6][%cal Yc2c4,Yb2b4,Yh2h3,Yg2g4,Yc4c5,Yb7b6,Yf7f5,Yg7g6,Gf8g7,
Gg7h6,Gg7f6,Gf6g5,Ye5e4,Ya6a5,Yf3f4] Finally, we are seeing the structure
reached in the main line of the 8...h5 variation against the English Attack.
As the diagram shows, both sides have many ideas available, which makes this
variation very rich and highly interesting. Since attacking ideas on the
kingside are not so easy, White provokes a transformation in the pawn
structure with Nd5. We have seen a similar idea in the first database, but the
pawns on f3 and h5 make the positions very different. White's main plan is to
use his queenside majority by means of b2-b4 followed by c4-c5. Another idea
is to grab space on the kingside with h3-g4-g5, or prepare the f2-f4 advance,
opening lines for the bishop pair. Normally, White should play some
preparatory moves before going for concrete actions, as he needs all his
pieces well placed once the tension grows up. For Black, it is important have
all the aforementioned ideas in mind, trying to avoid them if possible. For
this reason, b7-b6 is a normal way to keep the queenside safe. Also, the
advance a6-a5 can be played in some positions, but in this case, he should pay
attention to the newly weakened b5-square where White will likely install his
knight by means of the maneuver Na1-c2-a3-b5. Black has his own majority on
the other side where ideas like e5-e4 or f7-f5 might create appropriate
counterplay. If possible, Black should try to exchange the dark-squared
bishops. This bishop is a very important piece for White here, as after its
exchange the ideas on the queenside are less effective. Furthermore, the
weak-squares on the kingside become a problem, especially because the Black's
knights are ready to exploit them. Black can achieve this goal by means of
Kh7-Ng8-Bh6 or Nh7-Bf6-g5. Compared to the structures examined until now, this
one leads to complicated positional battles with chances for both sides.}  *

