1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. f3
h5 $5 9. Nd5 $5 {This move became popular recently. White used to wait a bit
to go for the structural transformation.} (9. Qd2 Nbd7 10. Nd5 {normally
transposes, but Black also has the option of} Nxd5 11. exd5 Bf5 12. Bd3 Bxd3
13. Qxd3 {leading to more simplified positions, but with similar ideas,
although White's attacking plans somehow look more dangerous now.}) 9... Bxd5 (
{The point is that if} 9... Nxd5 10. exd5 Bf5 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 {[%cal
Yd1d3] , White has saved a tempo compared to the previous note.}) 10. exd5 Nbd7
11. Be2 (11. Qd2 g6 12. O-O-O $5 {is another ambitious option. Normally it
comes with a pawn sacrifice by White after} Nb6 13. Kb1 $1 Nbxd5 14. Bg5 Be7
15. Bd3 {The game has changed now. White tries to exploit his lead in
development and open lines for the bishops to get some initiative, but Black
should be ok with the following plan.} Qc7 16. Rhe1 Nb6 $1 {Black wants to
castle queenside too, but first he needs to defend against c4-c5-ideas in
advance.} 17. Qe2 O-O-O $1 $13 {Salgado Lopez,I (2643)-Yilmaz,M (2624)/TUR-chT
Ankara 2018 (5.5)/1/2-1/2}) (11. c4 {normally transposes, but the text is more
accurate as we will see.}) 11... g6 $1 {Of course d6 is not a problem now, so
the bishop will be better developed on g7 or h6.} 12. Qd2 (12. O-O $6 {would
be imprecise in view of} Bh6 $1) 12... Bg7 13. O-O (13. Na5 $6 {is an attempt
to prevent b7-b6 and thus cramp Black's queenside.} Qc7 14. c4 {[%cal Yb2b4]
White looks to accelerate his queenside play, but Black has a strong idea now.}
e4 $1 15. O-O (15. f4 Ng4 $1 16. Bxg4 hxg4 17. O-O f5 $15 {[%cal Yd7c5,Yc5d3]
is already easier for Black.}) 15... exf3 16. gxf3 $5 {[%csl Ye4,Yg4] White
prefers to keep e4 and g4 under control.} O-O 17. b4 Rfe8 18. Rac1 {and now}
Rxe3 $1 {A brilliant positional sacrifice.} 19. Qxe3 Re8 $36 {[%cal Gc7b6,
Gg7h6,Yd7e5] , and Black had nice initiative for the exchange in Caruana,F 
(2844)-Gelfand, B (2748)/Baku FIDE GP 2014 (2)/1/2-1/2.}) 13... b6 $5 {[%csl
Ya5,Yc5] Prophylaxis against both Na5 and c4-c5.} (13... a5 $6 {Seems dubious.
After} 14. a4 $1 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Ye2b5,Yc2c4] White has the nice b5-square
for the bishop. Now we can see the advantage of keeping the c-pawn on its
initial square for a while. Carlsen,M (2842)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2779)/Biel GM
51st 2018 (7)/1/2-1/2}) 14. c4 (14. a4 {White tried this different plan in a
few games.} O-O 15. a5 b5 16. c4 $6 {, but after} bxc4 17. Bxc4 Qc7 18. Rfc1
Qb7 {[%csl Yd5] , and White was the one with problems in Battulga,N (2421)
-Cheparinov,I (2715)/Olympiad-43 Batumi 2018 (3.22)/0-1.}) 14... O-O 15. Rac1 {
[%cal Yb3a1,Gb2b4] White needs to vacate the a1-square to put the queenside
pawns in motion.} Re8 {The rook is always useful on the e-file.} ({If Black
plays} 15... a5 {immediately, White has an easy choice of plan.} 16. Na1 {
[%csl Gb5][%cal Ya1c2,Yc2a3,Ya3b5] and the knight heads b5.}) 16. Rfd1 $6 {
I have the impression that White just wants to play a "normal" move. But there
is no reason to place this rook on d1.} (16. Na1 $6 {looks bad now in view of}
e4 $1 {[%cal Ge8e1]} 17. f4 Ng4 $1 18. Bxg4 hxg4 {[%cal Yf7f5,Yd7c5,Yc5d3] ,
and Black is fine.}) ({But} 16. h3 $5 {is a nice move because it prevents
e5-e4 and White can count on g4-ideas at some moment.} Rc8 $5 {Black has an
interesting idea in mind keeping the pawn on a6} (16... e4 $2 17. f4 $18 {
[%cal Yb3d4]}) 17. Na1 $6 h4 $1 {[%cal Gf6h5]} 18. Bg5 e4 $1 19. f4 (19. Bxh4
exf3 20. Bxf3 Ne4 $1 {is a nice resource for Black.} 21. Qe1 Ng5 22. Qg3 Bf6
23. Bxg5 Bxg5 $15) 19... b5 $1 {[%cal Gd8b6] , and Black took the initiative
in Setyaki,A (2316) -Tomczak,J (2614)/Olympiad-43 Batumi 2018 (2.3)/0-1}) 16...
a5 {Now this is possible.} 17. h3 {This prevents the e4-advance and White can
consider g2-g4 in some positions, although this makes more sense with a rook
on f1.} (17. Na1 e4 $1 {Black is practically one tempo ahead now, which makes
this move stronger.} 18. Nc2 exf3 19. gxf3 (19. Bxf3 Ne4 $36) 19... Qe7 {
, and Black's position seems already easier, for example} 20. b3 Nh7 21. Re1
Bb2 $1 22. Rb1 Qf6 $15) 17... Nh7 $1 {[%cal Yg7f6,Yf6g5] Sasikiran shows good
understanding of the structure: Right after White plays h3, weakening more
dark-squares on the kingside, he prepares the exchange of the dark-squared
bishops.} 18. Na1 ({Maybe White should admit the mistake and go back.} 18. Rf1
$5) 18... h4 $1 {[%csl Yf4,Yg2,Yg3] Black fixes the dark squares on the
kingside - the beginning of a very effective plan.} 19. Nc2 Ndf6 $5 (19... Bf6
{was already good, but Black wants to bring as more pieces as possible to the
kingside before exploiting the dark squares.}) 20. Bf1 $2 {White watches
passively while Black consistently realizes his plan. Of course this is not a
good decision.} (20. b4 $5 {would be a better try to complicate matters.})
20... Nh5 21. b3 Bf6 22. Qf2 Rb8 23. Na3 Bg5 $15 {Black achieved his strategic
goals while keeping White's play on the queenside under control, which makes
his position already pleasant.} 24. Nb5 Bxe3 25. Qxe3 Nf4 26. Re1 $2 (26. Qe1
$5 {would have at least prevented the next idea.} Qf6 $15 {[%cal Yb8d8]}) 26...
Nf6 $1 {The second knight approaches the kingside now. Each move makes White's
position harder to play.} 27. Nc3 N6h5 28. Ne2 {This exchange doesn't solve
White's problems, but two knights to deal with would mean even more problems.}
(28. a3 Ng3 29. Ne4 Nf5 $17 {[%cal Yf5d4]}) 28... Nxe2+ 29. Bxe2 Kg7 {[%csl
Ye2,Gh5] Black's strategy was a complete success: His knight is much better
than the opponent's bishop. The kingside is full of weaknesses and it is a
matter of time until the central pawns start to move, putting White under
annoying pressure.} 30. Bf1 Ng3 31. Bd3 f5 $1 {The worst thing for White is
that he has no counterplay here.} 32. Rcd1 ({For example} 32. f4 $2 {makes
things even easier for Black.} e4 33. Bf1 Qc7 34. Rc2 Qc5 $1 {The endgames are
easily winning for Black.} 35. Rf2 Qxe3 36. Rxe3 g5 $1 37. fxg5 Kg6 {[%cal
Yg6g5,Gf5f4]}) 32... Qf6 33. Bc2 e4 $1 {The passed pawn is powerful enough to
decide the game.} 34. fxe4 (34. f4 {White is not able to prevent Black from
opening the position by force:} Rec8 {[%cal Yb6b5]} 35. a4 Kh6 36. Rd4 g5 $1
37. Rd2 Rg8 {[%cal Yg5g4]}) 34... fxe4 35. Rd2 Re5 $19 {[%cal Yb8e8,Yb8f8] At
this point White is already lost.} 36. Rf2 (36. a3 Rf5 37. Qd4 Rf8 38. Qxf6+
