0,22,-1,35,6,35,35,97,97,110,128,71,76,179,153,193,193,336,336,336,336,475,303,
380,380,1081,1204]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3
$5 {[%cal Yg2g4] This is currently one of the main lines against the Najdorf,
and very popular between grandmasters; basically, you can find games of any
2700+ player who enters the Najdorf with this move. Curiously, according to
the opening databases, it is called "Adams Attack", not because of the famous
English GM, but the Adams who played this move for the first time, back in
1948(!). Later some nice wins by Fischer seriously put the line into
tournament practice. White's goal could not be clearer: he wants to play g2-g4,
like in the Keres Attack. We will start dealing with the most aggressive
set-ups for White, with 0-0-0.} e6 {Accepting the challenge. Although this
leads to sharp positions, I like Black's chances. Nevertheless, this is the
preferred option by grandmasters.} ({The typical Najdorf move is} 6... e5) (
6... g6 $5 {should be also playable if Black wants to avoid the most
theoretical lines.}) 7. g4 Nfd7 $1 {I think this is the most accurate move
order, but the reason will become clear only when the opening stage reaches
its critical moment. The most obvious point of this retreat is that Black
wants to prepare the development move Nc6 without fearing e5-ideas.} 8. g5 (8.
Be3 {is likely to transpose after} b5 9. a3 Bb7 10. h4 Be7 11. g5) ({Another
option for White is to restrict the counterplay on the queenside with} 8. Bg2
Be7 9. Be3 Nc6 10. Qe2 {This seems a more natural square for the queen.} (10.
Qd2 Nde5 {[%csl Yc4] By threatening to exploit the unprotected square c4,
Black accelerates his queenside play.} 11. b3 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 O-O 13. O-O-O b5 $1
14. Ne2 $5 Bb7 15. f4 Ng6 16. Rhf1 (16. f5 $2 Nh4 $17) 16... e5 $5 {A common
way to reduce the strength of White's kingside pawns.} 17. Be3 exf4 18. Nxf4
Ne5 19. Kb1 {Dominguez Perez,L (2717)-Topalov,V (2812) Sofia MTel Masters 5th
2009 (8) 1/2} a5 {This seems most natural. If White plays like in the game,}
20. Nd5 Bxd5 21. exd5 Bh4 $1 {prevents the idea g5-h4-h5, and Black has no
problems, for example} 22. Be4 (22. g5 $2 a4 {Apart from the queenside attack,
White will have problems with the g5-pawn.} 23. Bf3 axb3 24. cxb3 Re8 25. Be2
Rb8 26. Rc1 Ng6 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Ye8e5]}) 22... Re8 23. Bd4 a4 24. Bb2 Qe7 25.
Qd4 h6 $11) (10. h4 $5 {This is less frequent but playable: White mixes ideas.}
O-O 11. g5 Nde5 $1 {[%csl Yc4] Black takes advantage of the vulnerability of
c4 in order to accommodate his pieces.} 12. Qe2 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Nc6 14. Be3 Bd7
15. f4 Rc8 16. O-O-O Na5 {Black has enough counterplay here} 17. Kb1 Nc4 18.
Bc1 {Abdumalik,Z (2428)-Assaubayeva,B (2395) Wch U20 Girls 34th 2017 (6) 1-0}
Na3+ 19. Ka1 b5 $1 $13 {[%cal Yb5b4]}) 10... O-O 11. O-O-O Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Rb8 $5
{[%cal Yb7b5,Gg2a8] An important move that avoids some risks on the long
