272,289,0,0,0,0,0,0]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. a3
$5 {The history of how this move drew the attention of strong grandmasters is
curious. Karjakin played it against Giri in the first round of Tata Steel 2017,
and although the game was drawn, the move somehow attracted World Champion
Magnus Carlsen, who played it the next day to score a nice win against
Wojtaszek, one of the best Najdorf players in the world. Later, Karjakin
confessed in an interview he had no time to prepare against Giri, as he missed
his laptop charger in Moscow, and 6.a3 was just improvisation :) Anyway, this
timid advance found many adepts since then and practical experience showed
that it is not as harmless as it may look at first sight.} e5 {The most direct
way to test this line.} ({I will just restrict myself to say that moves like} 
6... e6 {(although this is recommended by Pavlovic in his book)}) ({and} 6...
g6 {Perez Ponsa,F (2556)-Quintiliano Pinto,R (2423) American Continental 14th
2018 (4) 1/2 give White the option of going for variations in which 6.a3 might
prove very useful. I even had big trouble trying to play in Dragon-style when
facing this move in tournament practice.}) 7. Nf5 $5 {I think this is the most
promising for White.} ({, but} 7. Nf3 {can also be considered. Compared to the
lines 6.Be3 e5 7.Nf3 and 6.Be2 e5 7.Nf3 seen in database 1, White has played
neither of the bishops yet, so they can develop in an optimal way.} Be7 8. Bc4
(8. Bg5 {seems harmless} Be6 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Nd5 {Short,N (2646)-Paravyan,D 
(2634) Moscow Nutcracker 2018 (3.4) 1-0} Nd7 {[%emt 0:00:01] This position is
very similar to one analyzed in chapter 5.} 11. Bc4 Rc8 12. Ba2 {[%csl Ya2]
Having the a2-square for the bishop might be considered a small improvement
for White, but I don't think it is enough to get even a minimal plus.} Nc5 $1
13. Qe2 O-O 14. O-O g6 15. Rfd1 Bg7 $132 {[%cal Yf7f5] Black achieves
counterplay on the kingside}) 8... O-O 9. O-O ({Anand tried to rush with} 9.
Bg5 Be6 10. Bxf6 {, but Black has} Bxc4 $1 {, preserving the more important
bishop.} 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Nd2 Be6 13. Nf1 Nd7 14. Ne3 Nf6 15. O-O Rac8 16. Qd3
Rc6 {[%cal Yf8c8] , and Black was fine in Anand,V (2782)-Nepomniachtchi,I 
(2729) Wch Rapid Riadh 2017 (12) 1/2}) 9... Be6 $5 {A small drawback of 6.a3
is that White does not have Bb3 in this position.} 10. Ba2 (10. Qd3 $5 {
is a subtle move order, threatening to take on e6 followed by Ng5-Qh3.} Qc8 $1
11. Ba2 Nbd7 {and Black is fine, for example} 12. Bg5 b5 13. Rfd1 Rb8 $132 {
[%cal Yb5b4]}) 10... b5 11. Re1 Re8 12. Bg5 Nbd7 13. Nd2 Rb8 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15.
Nf1 b4 $1 {White will face some problems exploiting the d5-square due to his
unstable queenside now.} 16. Nd5 bxa3 17. bxa3 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 Bg5 $1 {[%csl Ye3]
, preventing the knight from coming to d5 via e3. Black kept the balance in
Karjakin,S (2785)-Giri,A (2773) Tata Steel-A 79th 2017 (1) 1/2.}) ({On the
other hand, after} 7. Nb3 {and}) (7. Nde2 {I don't see how 6.a3 could help
