15. O-O-O Nc5 16. Qf3 Bxd2+ 17. Rxd2 Qc7 18. Kb1 O-O-O {, and Black is at
least fine.}) 14... Bh6 $1 {We have reached a position similar to
Demchenko-Areshchenko, but with fewer options for White.} 15. Kb1 Nc5 16. Qe2
Bxd2 17. Qxd2 Qxd2 18. Rxd2 Ne4 19. Re2 Nd6 $1 {Black's play seems to be
easier already, for example} 20. f4 Nc4 $15 {[%cal Yc4e3]} *

