{[%evp 0,11,29,34,44,66,94,57,57,30,30,26,66,22]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4
4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h4 $5 {"So people are trying literally everything
against the Najdorf?" was my first thought when I saw strong grandmasters play
this move. After checking some of these games though, I had to admit the line
is playable. It does not seem too dangerous for Black, but you always should
know what to do against such lines, in order to avoid falling into its little
tricks.} e5 {Again the most principled.} 7. Nb3 Be6 8. f4 $5 {As strange as it
may look, this is the main continuation.} (8. Bg5 {is harmless with the bishop
already on e6.} Nbd7 9. Qd2 {Caruana,F (2811) -Andriasian,Z (2585) PRO League
Stage rapid 2018 (7) 1-0} (9. a4 $6 {playing on both sides raises the
interesting question of where White intends to hide the king.} Rc8 10. h5 h6
11. Bh4 Be7 12. Bd3 {Lagarde,M (2591)-Huschenbeth, N (2560) Berlin Lasker 150
blitz op 2018 (8) 0-1} O-O 13. O-O Rc6 $17 {[%cal Yd8c7,Yf8c8] It is not clear
what White has achieved by pushing the h-pawn, but Black has the simple plan
of exerting maximum pressure on the c-file, with a sacrifice on c3 likely
coming.}) 9... h6 10. Be3 (10. Bxf6 Nxf6 11. O-O-O Be7 12. f3 Qc7 13. g4 d5 $1
14. exd5 O-O-O {, and Black is fine.}) 10... Ng4 $1 {Black has no problems
after the exchange of this bishop, for example} 11. O-O-O Be7 12. g3 Qc7 13.
Kb1 O-O 14. Nd5 Bxd5 15. exd5 Nxe3 16. Qxe3 f5 $13 {with chances for both
sides.}) 8... b5 $5 {This is a provocative and less played idea, but Black has
scored well with it.} 9. f5 {Of course White continues his march on the
kingside.} (9. fxe5 {looks harmless:} dxe5 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Bg5 Nbd7 12. a4
b4 13. Nd5 {Piorun,K (2651) -Grandelius,N (2647) Rilton Cup 47th 2017 (6) 1/2}
Bxd5 14. exd5 h6 15. Bxf6+ Nxf6 16. O-O-O Bd6 {Black has a solid blockade in
the centre and should be fine.} 17. Bd3 Kc7 18. Rhf1 Rhf8 $11) 9... Bc8 $1 {
[%csl Ge4][%cal Yc8b7] The e4-pawn may become a target now.} 10. g4 $1 (10. Bg5
{was played twice but looks harmless for Black.} Nbd7 11. g4 (11. Nd5 Bb7 12.
c4 $2 bxc4 13. Bxc4 Be7 {After this, once more White faces the problem "where
to put the king?".} 14. Qd3 {Nestorovic,N (2506)-Lapcevic,M (2358) SRB-chT
Ruma 2017 (5.4) 0-1} Nxd5 15. Bxd5 Bxd5 16. Qxd5 O-O 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 {White's
position is already very difficult, for example} 18. O-O-O Nf6 19. Qxd6 Qxd6
20. Rxd6 Nxe4 21. Rd5 Ng3 22. Re1 f6 $19) 11... Bb7 12. Qf3 Rc8 13. Bd3 {
Ali Marandi,C (2515)-Cheparinov, I (2703) TUR-chT Kocaeli 2017 (12.5) 0-1
Instead of the typical sacrifice on c3, Black had an easier path to get a nice
position now.} (13. O-O-O Be7 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15. g5 {Here Black has the the
same idea.} Rxc3 $1 16. Qxc3 Nxe4 17. Qe3 Nc3 $1 18. Qxc3 Bxh1 19. Bxb5+ axb5
20. Rxh1 h6 $1 21. Qc6+ Qd7 22. Qa8+ Qd8 23. Qc6+ $11) 13... h5 $1 14. gxh5 (
14. Bxf6 gxf6 $1 15. gxh5 Bh6 {[%csl Ge1]} 16. Rg1 Nb6 {[%cal Yb5b4]} 17. a3
Ke7 {Black has nice compensation for the pawn. Ideas like Na4-Nc4, Rxc3 or d5
have to be considered all the time}) 14... Be7 (14... Rxc3 $5 {This would be a
better version compared to the game.} 15. bxc3 Qc7 $44 {[%cal Yd6d5]}) 15. Rg1
(15. O-O-O Rxc3 $1 16. bxc3 Qc7 $44 {This is always good compensation for
Black.}) 15... Nxh5 16. O-O-O Nhf6 {Black is at least ok in this position, for
example} 17. Nd5 (17. Kb1 Rxc3 $1 18. bxc3 Qc7 19. Bc1 d5 $36) 17... Bxd5 18.
exd5 Nb6 19. Bf1 Qc7 20. c3 e4 $1 (20... b4 $2 21. Bxa6) 21. Qg3 Nbxd5 $13)
10... Bb7 11. Bg2 b4 $1 {Black would be in trouble without this move.} 12. Nd5
Nxd5 13. exd5 a5 {Both sides have advanced pawns on opposite sides, making the
situation very unusual. I think there is a dynamic balance on the board,
typical for Sicilian positions.} 14. a3 $5 {Ruiz Sanchez,O (2427)-Gordievsky,D
(2613) US Masters op 2017 (2) 0-1 This makes sense, but there are other
options too.} ({For example} 14. Be3 Nd7 15. Nd2 Rc8 $1 {, preventing Nc4.} 16.
Ne4 $6 Nb6 {[%csl Gd5]} 17. Bxb6 Qxb6 18. Qd2 a4 $1 $13 {[%cal Yb4b3] is a
nice way to make 0-0-0 less attractive for White.}) (14. Nd2 {[%cal Yd2e4] ,
trying to improve the knight quickly.} Nd7 15. Ne4 Qb6 $1 {[%csl Ye3] White
has to solve the problem of the bishop now.} 16. a3 $1 Be7 17. axb4 axb4 18.
Rxa8+ Bxa8 19. Qd3 Bb7 20. Be3 Qa5 {[%csl Yd5] 0-0 is impossible in view of
Ba6 and d5 is hanging. White has to find resources like} 21. Qb3 $1 Bxd5 22.
Nxd6+ $1 Bxd6 23. Qxd5 Qxd5 24. Bxd5 {, but even this endgame is not at all
clear, for example} Nf6 25. Bc6+ Ke7 26. g5 Ng4 27. Ba7 $5 Rc8 28. Be4 Rc4 29.
Bd3 Rf4 $132) 14... Be7 {This is probably more solid for Black than the game.}
15. g5 h6 $5 {Immediately exploiting White's kingside.} 16. axb4 (16. Qg4 hxg5
17. hxg5 Rxh1+ 18. Bxh1 Qb6 $132 {seems OK for Black.}) (16. Qh5 $6 {this move
seems strong, but after} Qc7 $1 {it's actually White who has some problems.}
17. Be4 a4 18. Nd2 b3 $1 19. cxb3 Nd7 $1 {, and Black is very active.} 20. b4
Qb6 $36) 16... axb4 17. Rxa8 Bxa8 18. gxh6 gxh6 (18... Bxh4+ $6 19. Kf1 gxh6
20. Qg4 $14 {[%csl Gb4,Gh4]}) 19. Qg4 $5 {Winning a pawn.} Nd7 20. Qxb4 Rg8 21.
Bf3 Qb6 $1 {Black will likely regain the material now.} 22. Qxb6 (22. Qa4 Bb7
23. Bxh6 Rg1+ 24. Rxg1 Qxg1+ 25. Ke2 Qh2+ 26. Kd1 Qg1+ 27. Ke2 Qh2+ $11 28. Kd3
$6 Qg3 {becomes dangerous for White.}) 22... Nxb6 {[%csl Yd5]} 23. Bxh6 Rh8 24.
Bg5 Bxd5 25. Bxd5 Nxd5 26. c4 $1 (26. Rg1 f6 {[%csl Rh4] and}) (26. Bxe7 Kxe7 {
[%cal Ye7f6] seem fine for Black.}) 26... Nc7 27. Bxe7 Kxe7 {Black should
regain the pawn now.} 28. Nd2 d5 $1 $11 {[%cal Ye7f6]} *

