-34,-118,-118,-109,-30,-62,-62,-144,-133,-126,-118,-118,-118,-118,-118,-112,
-107,-100,-94,-93,-19,-3,0,-79,-80,-80,-71,-106,-115,-142,-146,-146,-146,-157,
-90,-102,-91,-96,-83,-121,-118,-118,-110,-102,-89,-100,-88,-119,-131,-131,-126,
-137,-134,-150,-163,-163,-163,-176,-185,-173,-173,-179,-164,-186,-152,-155,
-153,-141,-145,-161,-159,-177,-177,-178,-152,-182,-207,-226,-215,-208,-208,
-208,-208,-244,-215,-249,-249,-249,-249]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bd3 $5 {I think this is one of the most interesting sidelines
against the Najdorf, still not fully explored. Although there are thousands of
games with this move, it has only become fashionable in recent years after
Nakamura used it to beat Vachier-Lagrave, if I'm not wrong. White's position
remains a bit flexible and he can change his plans depending on the set-up
chosen by Black.} (6. Nf3 $6 {I must admit that I don't really see the point
of this move. Maybe White is just trying to get a game? Anyway, as harmless as
it may look, a few GMs have tried this, so we can take a look.} Nbd7 $5 {
For sure this knight makes more sense on d7 than White's on f3.} (6... e5 $2 {
Maybe this is White's dream, as it leads to an improved version of other
theoretical lines. Unfortunately Black has many better options.}) (6... e6 $2
7. e5 $1 {gives a point to White's idea. Andreikin,D (2712)-Karjakin,S (2763)
Moscow Tal Memorial blitz 11th 2018 (13) 1/2}) 7. a4 (7. Bc4 $2 b5 $1 {is
simply better for Black.} 8. Bd5 Rb8 9. Nd4 Qc7 {[%cal Ye7e6]}) (7. Be2 e6 8.
O-O b5 9. Qd4 e5 $5 10. Qe3 Bb7 11. b4 Be7 {Black is fine, he has all the
pieces developed in a nice and typical way. Kheit,W (2223)-Gormally,D (2499)
Hastings Masters op 90th 2014 (1) 0-1}) 7... b6 (7... e6 8. a5 $1 {made
White's position already interesting. Popov,I (2611)-Idani,P (2588) Chigorin
Memorial 26th 2018 (5) 0-1}) 8. Bc4 e6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Nd4 $5 {Predke,A (2622)
-Bocharov,D (2533) RUS Cup final 2018 (1.3) 0-1} Qc8 {This seems good as the
queen goes away from some tricky sacrifices on e6.} (10... Nxe4 $2 11. Nxe4
Bxe4 12. Qe2 $1 {gives White a lot of initiative for the pawn.}) 11. Ba2 Be7
12. f3 O-O 13. Be3 Re8 {, and Black is fine, for example} 14. Qd2 (14. Qe2 d5
$5 {[%cal Ge8e1]}) 14... Bf8 15. Rad1 Qc7 16. Qf2 Rac8 $11) 6... g6 {Here a
Dragon set-up is a very good choice for Black, as the bishop on d3 doesn't
look good in these positions.} 7. Be3 {Lately, White has tried to transpose
into some sort of main line of the Dragon, with this strange bishop on d3. The
other options show that maybe this is the most promising and critical
continuation after all.} (7. f3 {is just a different move order.} Bg7 ({
Although it gives Black the extra option of} 7... Qb6 $5) 8. Be3) (7. O-O {
is the most played.} Bg7 8. Kh1 (8. f4 $2 {is a terrible blunder.} Qb6 9. Kh1
Qxd4 10. Bb5+ Nfd7 $1 $19) 8... O-O 9. f4 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Gf2f4,Gd1e1,Ge1h4]
This is the typical plan when White develops the bishop to d3, like in some
positions of the 6.f4 variation: Develop and attack on the kingside with the
moves f4-f5-Qe1-Qh4, but not necessarily in this order.} b5 $1 {Black should
play actively against this plan.} 10. Qe1 Bb7 11. Nf3 Nbd7 12. a3 (12. e5 $2
dxe5 13. fxe5 Ng4 {This is already better for Black.} 14. e6 Nc5 15. exf7+ Rxf7
16. h3 Nxd3 17. cxd3 Ne5 $1 18. Nxe5 Rxf1+ 19. Qxf1 Bxe5 $17 {[%csl Yb7,Gd3,
Ye5]}) (12. f5 Nc5 {, and White should take some measures to continue his
kingside play.} 13. a3 (13. Qh4 $2 b4 $1 14. Nd5 Nxd3 15. cxd3 Bxd5 16. exd5
Qd7 {, and Black is at least fine.} 17. fxg6 fxg6 $1 18. Qxb4 Nxd5 19. Qc4 e6
$11) {We have transposed to another type of opening. Black can now play} 13...
a5 $5 {, which seems good enough to get a nice position.} 14. fxg6 fxg6 15.
Bxb5 {Franzen,J (2345)-Karlsson,L (2515) Politiken Cup 11th 1989 (1) 1/2} Nfxe4
16. Bc4+ Kh8 $13 {The position is unbalanced but Black is active.}) 12... Nc5
13. f5 a5 $5 {transposes to 12.f5}) (7. h3 Bg7 8. Be3 O-O 9. O-O (9. Qd2 Nc6
10. O-O-O {This is a different way to go for opposite-castling positions, but
like in the regular Dragon, Black equalizes with} d5 $1 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bh6 {
Short,N (2660)-Gelfand,B (2695) Dortmund SuperGM 25th 1997 (4) 1/2} Bxh6 $5 13.
Qxh6 Rb8 {[%cal Yd8b6] Black has decent counterplay.}) 9... b5 $1 10. a3 Bb7 {
This seems just fine for Black. Compared to regular Dragon positions, he has a
much improved version.} 11. Qd2 Nbd7 12. Bh6 Nc5 13. Rfe1 e5 $1 14. Nf3 {
