2018 (7) 1-0} (11. Qd2 {Hammer,J (2621)-Hauge,L (2436) NOR-ch rapid 2018 (5) 1/
2} d5 $1 {This is a simple solution for Black.} 12. exd5 cxd5 13. Bd4 Rb8 14.
b3 Qd6 15. Qe3 Nd7 $11) 11... Qa5 $5 (11... d5 $2 {is bad now in view of} 12.
Na4 $1 {[%csl Yc5,Yd4]}) 12. Bc4 (12. Kh1 Rb8 13. b3 Nd7 14. Na4 Qxe1 15. Raxe1
Bb7 $11) 12... Rb8 13. Bb3 Nd7 14. Rd1 Nc5 $5 {Black should be on the path to
equalize, as} 15. Nd5 $5 {doesn't give White anything.} (15. Kh1 Qb4 {[%cal
Ya6a4]}) 15... Qd8 16. Bxc5 cxd5 17. Bd4 (17. Ba7 Rb7 {is similar}) 17... Bxd4+
18. Rxd4 Qb6 19. Qf2 dxe4 20. Rxe4 e6 $11) 9... O-O 10. O-O-O (10. O-O {
looks harmless. Again Black plays} d5 $1 {and has no problems.}) 10... d5 $1 {
The inclusion of the moves Bd3/a6 doesn't seem to be a problem for Black.
Actually White is the one who loses some ideas with the bishop blocking the
d-file.} 11. Nxc6 {As this position occurred only once in tournament practice,
many options haven't been tested yet.} (11. exd5 $146 Nxd5 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13.
Nxd5 cxd5 14. Bh6 (14. h4 $2 Rb8 $36 {is already dangerous for White.}) 14...
Bf6 $1 {This is a very interesting sacrifice.} 15. Bxf8 (15. Bg5 Bh8 $1 {
keeps the valuable bishop.}) 15... Rb8 $1 16. c3 (16. b3 {is clearly inferior
due to the weakening of the dark squares.} Kxf8 $44 {[%cal Yd8d6]}) 16... Kxf8
{[%csl Gb8,Gf6][%cal Yd8a5] This position is more dangerous for White than it
may look at first sight: Black has a very clear attacking plan in mind while
White lost the initiative and needs to adjust himself to the unpleasant role
of the defender.} 17. Kb1 Qa5 18. Ka1 (18. Rc1 $2 d4 $17) 18... Bd7 {Strange
as it may look, White doesn't have too many safe moves here.} 19. Bc2 $5 {
[%cal Yc2b3] Most logical, trying to consolidate the king's position.} (19.
Rhe1 $6 Ba4 $1 20. Bc2 Bxc2 21. Qxc2 d4 $1 {, and Black's initiative is very
