{[%evp 0,11,16,28,58,46,100,91,61,37,37,26,43,22]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4
cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Qf3 {In this chapter we will deal with early
queen moves. The text is the most played, and it seems the most promising for
White as well. One important point is that with the queen on f3, the thematic
e5-advance looks less attractive.} (6. Qe2 {White wants to play with 0-0-0 and
at some point transpose to 6.Bg5-like positions. But I think the typical
Najdorf move} e5 $1 {works nicely here.} 7. Nf5 $5 {The only way to justify
White's previous move.} (7. Nb3 {[%csl Ye2] In general terms the queen is not
well placed on e2 in such positions.} Be6 8. Bd2 {Another drawback: As the
queen is not on d2, the bishop needs to be developed here, in order to prevent
Rxc3-ideas in the next moves} Nbd7 9. O-O-O {Gormally,D (2477)-Van Delft,M 
(2393) London Classic op 2017 (9) 1-0} b5 $5 10. a3 Rc8 {Black has achieved a
normal and nice set-up, while it is not clear what White has achieved, for
example} 11. Rg1 $6 Qc7 12. g4 d5 $1 $36) 7... d5 $1 {The best way to test
White's idea.} 8. Bg5 d4 9. O-O-O (9. Bxf6 gxf6 $1 {Take a look at chapter 3 -
this is just a worse version of the 6.a3 line for White.} 10. O-O-O Bd7 $1 11.
