{[%evp 0,19,16,16,57,62,99,70,70,25,44,33,88,56,46,46,46,35,63,45,65,65]} 1. e4
c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. f3 h5 $5
{As we have seen in the previous chapter, this move succeeds in making White's
attempts to attack harder if he proceeds in a "normal" way. So the most
promising ideas for White involve a transformation of the pawn structure by
playing Nd5 at some point, and after the subsequent exchange (B or N x d5 -
exd5), the new structure is not exactly new to us (see chapter 8 of the first
database), but the presence of the pawn on h5 and some differences in the
piece placement make the position different, with its own features and
possibilities. White has more freedom and space after the exchange, and
although his main plan is to make use of the pawn majority on the queenside,
ideas on the kingside are not discarded, as the h5-pawn can become a hook for
an attack. Black should be aware of those ideas, keeping the queenside as safe
as possible and looking for timely counterplay on the kingside by advancing
the e- and f-pawns, and in some cases with h4-h3. Usually the game has a
positional character. I think the positions arising from this line are very
rich in resources and offer nice chances for both sides, with interesting and
double-edged positions.} 9. Qd2 (9. Nd5 $5 {is an interesting move order.} Bxd5
(9... Nxd5 10. exd5 Bf5 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 {The point is that White saved a
tempo in this position compared to the ones in which he plays Qd2.}) 10. exd5
Nbd7 11. c4 {[%csl Gd2][%cal Yb3d2,Yd2b1,Yb1c3] A few grandmasters tried to
exploit the fact that White has not played Qd2 yet, using this square to
improve the knight, although I think this is not enough to create problems for
Black.} (11. Qd2 {transposes to the main line.}) 11... g6 12. Bd3 (12. Be2 Bh6
$1 {The same idea works nicely here.} 13. Bxh6 Rxh6 14. Qd2 Rh8 15. O-O-O {
White was probably afraid of ideas like h4-Nh5-f4 in case of 0-0, but Black
can play on the queenside now with} a5 $1 16. Kb1 a4 17. Nc1 {Melnikov,D (2299)
-Korobov,A (2671) Chigorin Memorial 19th 2011 (1) 0-1} Nc5 $15 {[%csl Yc5]
[%cal Yf6d7] Black is fine.}) 12... Bh6 $1 {[%csl Gh6] This is a good
